I used to slay with this in code golfing competitions from TopCoder, where you had to implement a function to solve a particular problem, thanks to C pointer maths and the gcc generally putting function arguments in order in the stack.<p>Turns out, these two are equivalent in practice (but UB in the C++ standard):<p><pre><code>    double solve(double a, double b, double c, double d) {
      return a + b + c + d;
    }

    double solve(double a ...) {
      return a + 1[&amp;a] + 2[&amp;a] + 3[&amp;a];
    }</code></pre>
